On day six, I learnt about switching concepts and how switches forward data within a network. The lesson focused on MAC address tables, frame forwarding processes, and the different switching methods used to improve network communication and performance.

Topics Covered and What I Learnt
1. Switching in Networking

I learnt the role of switches in networking and how they help devices communicate within a Local Area Network (LAN). I understood that switches:

Connect multiple devices in a network
Forward data intelligently
Reduce unnecessary traffic
Improve network efficiency

This topic helped me understand the importance of switches in modern computer networks.

2. The Switch MAC Address Table

I learnt about the MAC address table, which stores MAC addresses and the corresponding switch ports connected to devices. I understood that:

Switches use MAC addresses to identify devices
The table helps switches forward frames correctly
MAC tables improve communication efficiency

This helped me understand how switches keep track of connected devices.

3. The Switch Learn and Forward Method

I learnt how switches use the learn and forward process to handle network traffic. I understood that:

A switch learns source MAC addresses from incoming frames
It stores these addresses in the MAC address table
The switch forwards frames only to the correct destination port when possible

This process reduces unnecessary traffic within the network.

4. Video – MAC Address Tables on Connected Switches

I watched a video demonstration showing how MAC address tables operate between connected switches. The video helped me visualize:

How switches exchange information
How MAC addresses are learnt dynamically
How communication flows across multiple switches

This improved my understanding of real network operations.

5. Switching Forwarding Methods

I learnt about different frame forwarding methods used by switches to transmit data. I understood how forwarding methods affect:

Network speed
Error handling
Overall performance

This introduced me to the advantages and disadvantages of different switching techniques.

6. Store-and-Forward Switching

I learnt that in store-and-forward switching:

The switch receives the entire frame before forwarding it
Error checking is performed before transmission
Corrupted frames can be discarded

I understood that this method improves reliability but may introduce slight delays.

7. Cut-Through Switching

I learnt that cut-through switching:

Begins forwarding a frame before the entire frame is received
Reduces latency and increases speed
Performs less error checking compared to store-and-forward switching

This helped me understand the trade-off between speed and error detection.

8. Activity – Switch It!

Finally, I completed an activity where I applied switching concepts practically. The activity helped me:

Understand frame forwarding processes
Analyse MAC address learning
Observe how switches make forwarding decisions

This practical exercise strengthened my understanding of switching operations and network communication.
